acy  ."]},{"name":"Lacey","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Lacy  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Countess Agnes de Lacy was born in 1080, in Knaresborough, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Count Robert I Valognes. She died about 1165, in Ewyas Harold, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 86."},"et":{"1080–about 1165":"1080–umbes 1165","1075–1161":"1075–1161","1108–1129":"1108–1129","1080–1165":"1080–1165","1080":"1080","1129":"1129","about 1129":"umbes 1129","about 1108":"umbes 1108","1165":"1165","1075":"1075","about 1165":"umbes 1165","1161":"1161","29 June 1161":"29. juuni 1161","1108":"1108","Knaresborough Castle, Yorkshire, England.":"Knaresborough, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ewyas-Harold, Herefordshire, England.":"Ewyas Harold, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England":"Ellenhall, Staffordshire, England","Parham Castle, Plomesgate, Sussex, England.":"Par